{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"015719d9-e8ea-4670-b47d-b2aea76b49e1","content":"On macOS, the OS automatically generates **`.ips` crash reports** when a process crashes. You don't need `createdump`.\n\n**Where to find them:**\n\n- **`~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`** — crash reports for your user\n- **`/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`** — system-wide crash reports\n\nLook for a file named like `YourAppName-YYYY-MM-DD-HHMMSS.ips`.\n\n**Quick lookup:**\n\n```bash\nls -lt ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/*.ips | head\n```\n\nYou can also open **Console.app → Crash Reports** to browse them in a GUI.\n\n**Core dumps** (if enabled via `ulimit -c unlimited`) go to `/cores/core.<pid>`, but `.ips` reports are usually sufficient and always available.\n\n> 💡 If you need to symbolicate the .NET runtime frames in the `.ips` file, let me know — I can help with that using the **apple-crash-symbolication** skill.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"ba280d78-e466-4cbc-ae37-88c80c8c38d9","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, without `createdump`. This is a knowledge question — I don't need to search a codebase. Let me answer directly.","outputTokens":324,"requestId":"7643:31275C:E7337E:10E50D1:69FE925A"},"id":"cacbf722-ec05-48ba-a3f1-d0912661fd42","timestamp":"2026-05-09T01:48:19.795Z","parentId":"3dc458b2-cd82-4e99-85e7-db68208011fb"}
